  <thingsToDo><![CDATA[<h3>Discover the town of Kamnik</h3>
<p>Kamnik is a medieval town rich in history, and it's easy to spend a day discovering the best bits of the town, from the pretty streets lined with artisan workshops, to the remains of the two castles. The small chapel on Mali Grad Hill is all that remains of the first castle, which is one of the most iconic views in Kamnik and the Stari Grad castle remnants are a popular walking spot, only 30 minutes from the town but offering one of the most picturesque panorama's of surrounding valleys and peaks. Take a trip into Kamnik's history at the Kamnik Regional Museum in the Zaprice Manor or stop by the Mili Vrh guesthouse for some of the best local food in town - it's on the outskirts of Kamnik but is worth the wander.</p>
<h3>Velika Planina</h3>
<p>Thought to be one of the most beautiful Alpine pastures in Slovenia, the Velika Planina is an ancient karst plateau, dotted with around 200 traditional herder's huts. Herder's take their cattle here at the start of June and stay for the summer, the most experienced cow leads the way with a bell round its neck, and at the end of the grazing season, the herder presents his partner some Trnič cheese as a symbol of his love and loyalty to her. Get a glimpse into herding life in the 19th Century in the Preskar Museum Hut or visit the Snow Mary Chapel. As well as the history and tradition on the plateau, you'll enjoy some of the best views of the Kamnik-Savinja Alps.</p>
<h3>Volčji Potok Arboretum</h3>
<p>No matter what time of year you visit the botanical gardens at <span>Volčji Potok Arboretum, you're in for a treat. They have been declared a cultural monument of national importance for it's contribution to the horticultural and architectural heritage of Slovenia, and there's nearly 5,000 species of plants and trees, all meticulously well looked-after. With 86 hectares to explore, it's perfect for leisurely strolls and admiring of plants including 1,200 rose varieties. Don't worry, there's plenty to keep the children entertained too - a large adventure playpark has slides, swings and climbing frames - can you find your way to the middle of the maze?</span></p>
<h3>Tuhinja Valley</h3>
<p>In this quiet, rural valley you'll be at one with nature, exploring the gentle valley paths, romantic forests and pastures - people have made a living from farming here for many years. Several marked paths lead up to the Alpine pastures of the Menina Plateau - a sub-alpine karst plateau with hidden caves and sinkholes, it's a peaceful spot to enjoy a walk - find your way to the secret peak for some incredible views. The valley is also home to the Snovik Spa, the highest altitude spa in Slovenia, where you can relax the day away and enjoy some me-time.</p>
<h3><span>Kamniška Bistrica</span></h3>
<p>One of the cleanest rivers in Slovenia flows the length of Kamniška Bistrica Valley, the pristine waters are perfect for a paddle. Discover springs and gorges, or head into one of the side valleys to see the 30-metre high Orglice Waterfall - keep an eye out for eagles on this walk as they used to nest in the cliffs by the falls.</p>
<p><span>At the head of the valley, keen hiker's can embark on Kamnik's must-do hike for the locals - it's said that everyone from Kamnik must visit the Kamnik Saddle at least once in their lives - it's easy to see why, a beautiful walk is rewarded with spectacular views down the valley and tasty food in the mountain hut.</span><span></span></p>
<h3>Biking in Kamnik</h3>
<p>Exploring Kamnik on two wheels is just as good as on two feet - it's a paradise for cyclists. Whether you head into the Kamniška Bistrica Valley and cycle along the trail to the river head, or tackle some of the more challenging trails in the forest, you'll definitely have a smile on your face. Or, challenge yourself to the ascent to the Velika Planina plateau - if you don't fancy the steep ascent by bike or foot, you can hop on the cable-car instead, but it is a rewarding climb. </p>]]></thingsToDo>
